      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How many miscarriages do I need before I can get a workup?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Major professional societies define recurrent pregnancy loss as two or more clinical pregnancy losses, and evaluation is recommended at that threshold. In an RRM-oriented approach, evaluation can begin after a single loss when risk factors are present: age over 35, a pattern of cycle irregularity, a short luteal phase on charting, known thyroid disease, known endometriosis, or a partner whose semen has not been analyzed. Waiting for a third loss is not a clinical standard. It is a practice pattern. The rationale for waiting is that many first miscarriages are chromosomally abnormal and do not recur. That is true. It does not tell you whether a treatable cause is also present. An evaluation after the first or second loss does not assume the cause is complex. It finds out whether one exists. A basic evaluation, including cycle charting, thyroid panel, progesterone timing, and partner semen analysis, is low-risk and high-information. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
