    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What are the most common treatable causes of recurrent miscarriage?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'The most consistently documented treatable causes are: chronic endometritis, luteal phase deficiency, thyroid dysfunction (including elevated TSH within the conventional "normal" range and autoimmune thyroid disease), antiphospholipid syndrome, anatomic factors (uterine septum, submucosal fibroids, endometrial polyps), hypoandrogenemia and low DHEA-S, and sperm DNA fragmentation in the male partner. Endometriosis is an independent contributing factor. Many of these are not tested on the standard RPL panel. Chronic endometritis requires endometrial biopsy with specific immunohistochemistry staining. Hypoandrogenemia requires androgen testing that most RPL workups do not include. The practical implication: a "normal" standard workup may not have looked for the actual cause. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
