        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Chronic endometritis is a documented and treatable contributor to recurrent miscarriage. In a study of 360 women with unexplained recurrent miscarriage, 56.7% had CE confirmed by hysteroscopy and histology. Among women whose CE was successfully treated and confirmed cured, 78.4% achieved pregnancy within one year, compared to approximately 17.5% in women with persistent CE or no CE diagnosis. Chronic endometritis is asymptomatic in most women. There is no fever, no obvious sign, no reason to suspect it from a routine visit. It is diagnosed by endometrial biopsy with CD138 immunohistochemistry staining, not by pelvic exam or standard ultrasound. If prior RPL workup did not include endometrial biopsy, chronic endometritis has not been excluded. For a dedicated guide to CE, see our page on chronic endometritis. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
