      name: 'Does endometriosis cause miscarriage?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Endometriosis is an independent risk factor for pregnancy loss, not only for infertility. A 2016 retrospective cohort study found that women with histologically proven endometriosis had a significantly higher rate of prior spontaneous miscarriage than endometriosis-free controls (adjusted IRR 1.70, 95% CI 1.34 to 2.16). A 2017 study found that endometriosis, particularly mild disease (rASRM Stage I to II), was associated with a miscarriage rate of 42.1% vs. 22.0% in controls. The mechanisms include endometriosis-associated luteal phase deficiency, the inflammatory pelvic milieu, and impaired endometrial receptivity. Women with recurrent loss who also have cyclical pelvic pain, dysmenorrhea, premenstrual spotting, or a history of deep dyspareunia should be evaluated for endometriosis as a contributing cause. If endometriosis is present and goes unaddressed, the conditions for recurrent loss may persist. A detailed guide to endometriosis is available on this site. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'I had a miscarriage after IVF. What might have been missed?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'A miscarriage after IVF does not mean the pre-IVF evaluation was complete. IVF workup focuses on ovarian response, egg retrieval, embryo development, and transfer logistics. The uterine environment, the cycle-specific hormonal support, the presence of chronic endometritis, and the luteal phase data are not routinely addressed. Chronic endometritis is disproportionately common in women who have undergone repeated uterine procedures. An embryo transferred to an inflamed endometrium will not implant successfully regardless of chromosomal status. After a post-IVF miscarriage, the appropriate question is not only "what was wrong with the embryo" but "what has not yet been evaluated in the uterine environment?" That includes endometrial biopsy for CE, a full thyroid panel, androgen testing, cycle-timed progesterone review, and partner sperm DNA fragmentation testing if not already done. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'At my age, are the odds against me anyway?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Age affects the proportion of chromosomally abnormal pregnancies, and that proportion increases year by year into the fifth decade. That is clinically accurate. It is not the complete picture. Treatable causes of recurrent miscarriage are not age-exempt. Chronic endometritis, thyroid dysfunction, luteal phase deficiency, hypoandrogenemia, and sperm DNA fragmentation are present in women of all ages. In a cause-based treatment study, women 40 and older with recurrent pregnancy loss who received multifactorial evaluation and treatment achieved a 55.6% live birth rate in subsequent pregnancies, compared to 30.0% in untreated controls of the same age, a clinically meaningful difference even without formal statistical significance in that cohort. Those numbers are not a guarantee. They are evidence that evaluation and treatment improve outcomes even after 40. The age discussion belongs in the context of a full evaluation, not before it. What "the odds" are before anyone has looked is not a number worth accepting. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
