      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'The answer depends on what the evaluation finds and what the treating clinician determines. Progesterone support, when indicated, is typically used in the luteal phase and through the first trimester, until the placenta is producing sufficient progesterone on its own. Duration and approach vary by clinical indication. No specific protocol is appropriate to state here; this is a conversation between the patient and her clinician. What is worth knowing: progesterone support, when prescribed because evaluation identified a luteal phase deficiency or low progesterone levels, is not a precautionary measure applied without reason. It is a response to a documented finding. If progesterone support has been recommended without prior luteal phase or progesterone evaluation, that is worth asking about. The treatment should follow the finding. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
