      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the chance of a healthy pregnancy after recurrent loss?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'This depends on whether the cause has been identified and treated. For women who received cause-based multifactorial evaluation and treatment in one well-documented cohort, the corresponding live birth rate was approximately 78.1% for those under 40 and 55.6% for those 40 and older. In a NaPro-treated cohort of couples with recurrent miscarriage, the cumulative adjusted proportion of live births over 24 months was 66 per 100 couples, in a population with an average female age of 35.4 years. For couples with three or more prior miscarriages who received NaPro treatment in Ireland, live birth rates in those who conceived were 80.6%, against a background expected miscarriage rate above 30 to 40% in that population. These are not promises. They are outcomes from real couples with documented histories, evaluated systematically, with causes treated when found. The probability without evaluation, without finding and addressing causes, is lower. That is the case for evaluation. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is genetic testing of the products of conception worth doing?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Genetic testing of the products of conception identifies whether the lost pregnancy was chromosomally abnormal. In many cases, this is useful information, but it comes with an important caveat. When the loss is chromosomally abnormal, some clinicians use that as a conclusion: "the miscarriage happened because the embryo was abnormal; this is expected and not a sign of a recurrent problem." That reasoning has limits. An abnormal embryo does not exclude a concurrent treatable cause in the uterine environment. Older eggs produce more chromosomal errors. Age-related aneuploidy is itself a clinical finding. And an inflamed or hormonally unprepared endometrium creates conditions in which even genetically normal embryos may fail. POC testing is useful information. It does not close the workup. Parental karyotyping is separately indicated in couples with recurrent loss where a balanced chromosomal rearrangement in a parent may be the underlying cause. This is a different test from POC analysis and requires a different clinical discussion. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
  ],
};
