          <aside class="editing-notice" role="status" aria-label="Editor's note">
            <p><strong>Editor's note:</strong> This guide is being actively edited. Content and citations may change over the next few days.</p>
          </aside>

          <aside class="disambig" aria-label="Disambiguation">
            <p>A note on related terms: "chemical pregnancy," "early pregnancy loss," "clinically recognized miscarriage," and "recurrent pregnancy loss (RPL)" are related but distinct clinical categories. This guide covers all of them, from the first loss to recurrent loss, and explains how evaluation differs at each stage. No other common condition shares a confusable name with miscarriage, so no cross-link disambiguation is needed.</p>
          </aside>

          <aside class="tldr">
            <h2 id="key-takeaways">Key Takeaways</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Miscarriage affects approximately 15% of clinically confirmed pregnancies and is the most common adverse pregnancy event.</strong> Recurrent pregnancy loss, defined as two or more clinical pregnancy losses, affects an estimated 2 to 5% of couples trying to conceive. Most causes are diagnosable. Most are treatable, per <a href="/library/does-a-short-luteal-phase-correlate-with-an-increased-risk-of-miscarriage-a-coho-recsypcebszclpsk1/">Duane et al. 2022</a>.</li>
              <li><strong>Major professional societies define recurrent pregnancy loss as two or more clinical losses and recommend evaluation at that threshold.</strong> In practice, many women still encounter the three-loss rule in their first clinical encounter. The gap is not in the guideline. It is in how guidelines translate into community practice. RRM-trained clinicians begin evaluation after the first loss when risk factors are present. Waiting is not clinically necessary, per <a href="/library/recurrent-pregnancy-loss-recshg1nt4mlkcm0b/">ASRM 2012</a> (reaffirmed 2020, updated 2026).</li>
              <li><strong>Chronic endometritis is found in approximately 56.7% of women with recurrent miscarriage</strong>, and treatment substantially improves subsequent pregnancy rates. It is rarely included in a standard miscarriage workup. In a study of 360 women with unexplained recurrent miscarriage, antibiotic treatment of confirmed CE led to a 78.4% subsequent pregnancy rate in women whose CE was cured, compared to approximately 17.5% in women with persistent CE or no CE on biopsy, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-due-to-common-bacteria-is-prevalent-in-women-with-recurrent-recyfpe9a4szxychl/">Cicinelli et al. 2013</a>.</li>
              <li><strong>Elevated TSH, even within the "normal" range, is independently associated with higher pregnancy loss rates.</strong> In a prospective study of over 4,000 women, those with TSH between 2.5 and 5.0 mIU/L had a significantly higher pregnancy loss rate than those with TSH below 2.5 (6.1% vs. 3.6%). Thyroid antibody status is a separate variable. Both matter, per <a href="/library/increased-pregnancy-loss-rate-in-thyroid-antibody-negative-women-with-tsh-levels-reculphjam60qtljh/">Negro et al. 2010</a>.</li>
              <li><strong>Sperm DNA fragmentation is significantly elevated in male partners of women with recurrent pregnancy loss.</strong> A systematic review and meta-analysis found that sperm DNA fragmentation rates are substantially higher in partners of women with RPL compared to fertile controls. The male partner is a clinical variable. Workup that ignores him is incomplete, per <a href="/library/sperm-dna-fragmentation-and-recurrent-pregnancy-loss-a-systematic-review-and-met-recyq3m4kcw20pwot/">McQueen et al. 2019</a>.</li>
              <li><strong>Age matters, but it is not the whole answer.</strong> In a cause-based treatment cohort addressing thyroid function, endometritis, immune factors, and thrombophilia, women under 40 achieved a 78.1% live birth rate after treatment (derived from a 21.9% miscarriage rate in treated women vs. 57.7% in untreated controls, p=0.002). Women 40 and older achieved 55.6% vs. 30.0%, a clinically meaningful difference that did not reach formal statistical significance in the cohort studied. Neither group was told "it just happens." Both groups had diagnosable, treatable contributing factors, per <a href="/library/novel-approaches-to-the-management-of-recurrent-pregnancy-loss-the-optimum-optim-recotwemmxon5hm20/">Kuroda et al. 2021</a>.</li>
            </ul>
          </aside>

          <section id="what-is-miscarriage">
            <h2>What Is Miscarriage? Defining the Terms</h2>

            <p class="pillar-lead"><strong>Miscarriage is the spontaneous loss of a pregnancy before viability. It is the most common adverse event in pregnancy. It is also one of the most commonly under-investigated. Women are told it is normal, that it is bad luck, that the body knew what it was doing. Some of that is partially true. None of it is a substitute for a clinical answer.</strong></p>

            <p>The terminology matters because it shapes what gets evaluated and when.</p>

            <p><strong>Chemical pregnancy</strong> refers to a pregnancy confirmed biochemically by rising and then falling hCG, before ultrasound can visualize a gestational sac. Many women experience these and are told they were not "real" miscarriages. Clinically, a chemical pregnancy represents a conception that implanted and then failed. It warrants attention if it recurs.</p>

            <p><strong>Clinically recognized miscarriage</strong> refers to pregnancy loss after ultrasound visualization of an intrauterine gestational sac. This is the category most commonly counted in clinical literature. The 15% figure, the most commonly cited miscarriage rate, applies here: approximately 15% of clinically confirmed pregnancies end in spontaneous loss, per <a href="/library/does-a-short-luteal-phase-correlate-with-an-increased-risk-of-miscarriage-a-coho-recsypcebszclpsk1/">Duane et al. 2022</a>. First-trimester losses account for the large majority. Second-trimester losses are less common and carry a distinct differential.</p>

            <p><strong>Early pregnancy loss</strong> is sometimes used interchangeably with first-trimester miscarriage, referring to loss before 13 weeks.</p>

            <p><strong>Late pregnancy loss</strong> refers to loss between 13 and 20 weeks of gestation. This category has a different clinical differential: anatomic factors, cervical incompetence, thrombophilia, and maternal infection are more prominent. Late loss is less common and demands its own workup.</p>

            <p><strong>Recurrent pregnancy loss (RPL)</strong> is defined by major professional societies as two or more clinical pregnancy losses, not necessarily consecutive. The 2026 update from a major professional society further broadened this definition to include hCG-confirmed biochemical pregnancies. Prevalence is estimated at 2 to 5% of couples trying to conceive, per <a href="/library/recurrent-pregnancy-loss-recshg1nt4mlkcm0b/">ASRM 2012</a> (reaffirmed 2020, updated 2026).</p>

            <p>That definition matters. Two losses is not a borderline case. It is a clinical signal that warrants evaluation. The question is not whether to investigate. The question is whether the investigation is thorough enough.</p>

            <p>Miscarriage is not one thing. It is a clinical outcome with multiple causes. "You had a miscarriage" is a description of what happened. It is not a diagnosis of why.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="diagnostic-gap">
            <h2>The Diagnostic Gap: Why Most Workups Start Too Late</h2>

            <p>Three losses. That was the historical threshold. Three clinical pregnancy losses before the system considered it a pattern worth investigating. Major professional societies moved to two losses more than a decade ago. That guideline shift is documented and formal. But guidelines and practice patterns are different things. Many women still encounter the three-loss expectation in their first clinical encounter.</p>

            <p>The rationale was probabilistic: a single miscarriage is common enough that it was considered unlikely to be a sign of a diagnosable problem. Two felt borderline. Three was the signal. What this logic fails to account for is that most causes of recurrent miscarriage are present and diagnosable after the first loss. A woman with chronic endometritis, subclinical hypothyroidism, or luteal phase deficiency does not acquire these conditions after her second miscarriage. She had them before the first one. Waiting for a third loss does not gather more clinical information. It generates more loss.</p>

            <p>Although <a href="/library/recurrent-pregnancy-loss-recshg1nt4mlkcm0b/">ASRM 2012</a> (reaffirmed 2020, updated 2026) defines RPL as two clinical losses and recommends evaluation at that threshold, practice patterns in community settings frequently defer workup further. RRM-trained clinicians begin evaluation after the first loss when risk factors are present: age over 35, prior miscarriage history, a short luteal phase on prior charting, thyroid symptoms, irregular cycle patterns, or a partner whose semen analysis has not been reviewed.</p>

            <p>This is not aggressive medicine. It is basic clinical logic. The causes of recurrent pregnancy loss are, in many cases, identifiable and treatable. The question is whether anyone looked.</p>

            <p>"Unexplained" recurrent miscarriage is the category assigned when standard workup finds nothing. The causes are not unexplained. They are undetected. Chronic endometritis, subclinical thyroid dysfunction, and luteal phase deficiency do not appear on the standard panel. They are not tested unless the clinician looks for them. What mainstream medicine calls "unexplained," RRM-trained clinicians call "not yet evaluated."</p>

